t this transformation is the result of a subnationally-rooted process driven by civil society actors, namely the Sanitarist Movement. He argues that their ability to leverage state-level political positions to launch a gradual but persistent attack on health policy implementation enabled them to infuse their social welfare ideology into the practice of Brazil's democracy. In so doing, Gibson illustrates how local activists can advance progressive social change more than predicted, and how in large democracies like Brazil, activists can both deepen the quality of local democracy and improve human development outcomes previously thought beyond their control.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCivil societyxBrazil. 0aCivil societyzBrazil. 0aCivil society. 0aDemocracyxBrazil. 0aDemocracyzBrazil. 0aDemocracy. 0aHealth Policy. 0aMedical policyxBrazil. 0aMedical policyzBrazil. 0aMedical policy. 0aMunicipal governmentxBrazil. 0aMunicipal governmentzBrazil. 0aMunicipal government. 0aPublic HealthxBrazil. 0aPublic healthxBrazil. 0aPublic healthxCitizen participationxBrazil. 0aPublic healthxCitizen participation. 0aPublic healthzBrazilxCitizen participation. 0aSocial movementsxBrazil. 0aSocial movementszBrazil. 0aSocial movements. 0aUrban Health. 0aUrban healthxBrazil. 0aUrban healthzBrazil. 0aUrban health. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh  aBrazil.  aLatin America.  acity politics.  acivil society.  ademocracy.  adevelopment.  ainfant mortality.  apolitical sociology.  apublic health.  asocial movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is 